# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1901-washington-senators-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-baltimore-orioles-season] The 1901 Baltimore Orioles season finished with the Orioles in 5th in the American League with a record of 68–65.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-baltimore-orioles-season] The team was managed by John McGraw and played at Oriole Park.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The **1901 Boston Americans season** was the first season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox, and the first season of play for the American League (AL).
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] It resulted in the Americans finishing second in the AL with a record of 79 wins and 57 losses, four games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] On February 11, Jimmy Collins, third baseman for the National League Boston Beaneaters became the first player under contract for the Boston Americans after being offered a contract of $4000 with the added ability to sign subsequent players to contracts.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Collins was joined on March 4 by the outfielder Chick Stahl, who was also from the Beaneaters.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Defecting with Stahl and Collins was the outfielder Buck Freeman.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Yet perhaps the most important signing was that of the 34 year old St.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Louis Cardinals pitcher Cy Young, who accepted a contract worth $3500 from the Boston Americans.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Vital to the signing of Cy Young from the Cardinals was the signing of Cy Young's catcher in St.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Louis, Lou Criger; the value that Young gave to Criger and that Criger gave to Young was so strong, that it is unlikely that Young would have signed for the Americans if Criger had not done so.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Charlottesville, Virginia.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The total attendance for the Red Sox was 289,448, the second most in the American League (behind the White Sox' 354,350) and more than the crosstown Boston Beaneaters' 146,502.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 12 home runs and had 114 RBIs while recording a .339 batting average.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 43 appearances (41 starts) and pitched 38 complete games with a 33–10 record and 1.62 ERA, while striking out 158 in 371+1⁄3 innings.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The team had two games end in a tie; August 31 at Detroit Tigers and September 12 at Washington Senators.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Tied games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tied games are counted.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Cy Young led the league in ERA (1.62), shutouts (5; tied with Clark Griffith), strikeouts (158), and wins (33).
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1901 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 31st season of the franchise.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-boston-beaneaters-season] The Beaneaters finished fifth in the National League with a record of 69–69.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-brooklyn-superbas-season] The **1901 Brooklyn Superbas** lost several players to the newly official major league, the American League.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-brooklyn-superbas-season] The Superbas finished third in the National League with a record of 79–57.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-orphans-season] The **1901 Chicago Orphans season** was the 30th season of the Chicago Orphans franchise, the 26th in the National League and the ninth at West Side Park.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-orphans-season] The Orphans finished sixth in the National League with a record of 53–86.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-orphans-season] The team was also known as the Remnants, due to many Orphans players leaving at the end of the 1900 season to join the upstart American League.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1901 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished in last place in the eight-team National League with a record of 52 wins and 87 losses, 38 games behind the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] The Cincinnati Reds continued to rebuild by adding younger players to their roster in 1901.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] They finished the 1900 season with a 62–77 record, finishing in seventh place in the National League.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] The team dismissed manager Bob Allen after only one season, and replaced him with Reds legend Bid McPhee.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] McPhee had played second base for Cincinnati from 1882 to 1899.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds acquired a new shortstop, as George Magoon joined the club.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] He last played in the majors in 1899, splitting time between the Baltimore Orioles and Chicago Orphans.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] Dick Harley, who played in only five games with the Reds in 1900, would get a starting job in left field.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] Harley's last full season was in 1899 with the Cleveland Spiders, when he hit .250 with a homer and 50 RBI.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] Sam Crawford was a bright spot for the team, as he batted .330 with a league high sixteen home runs, while driving in 104 runners to lead the team offensively.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] Jake Beckley was solid once again, hitting .307 with three home runs and 79 RBI.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, Noodles Hahn had a very solid season, going 22–19 with a 2.71 ERA.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] Hahn led the league with 41 complete games, 375.1 innings pitched, and striking out 239 batters.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] Bill Phillips, with a 14–18 record and a 4.64 ERA, was the only other Cincinnati pitcher to have ten or more victories.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati got the season off on a good note, as they won four of their first five games to take a very early first place lead in the National League.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds would continue to hold on to first place through twenty-three games in, as they had a 15–8 record, a one-game lead over the New York Giants.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] Even though Cincinnati went 5–6 in their next eleven games, they held on to a first place tie with the Giants before losing ten games in a row to fall to seventh place with a 20–24 record.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] Some of their losses were lopsided, as the Reds lost 25–13 to the Giants to begin their losing streak, and in their tenth loss, they were on the wrong side of a 21–3 pasting by the Brooklyn Superbas.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] After snapping their ten-game losing streak with a victory over the Philadelphia Phillies, the Reds lost four more in a row, including losses of 8–0 and 19–1 to the Phillies.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati continued to struggle for the rest of the season, falling into the cellar, and finished the year with a 52–87 record, 38 games behind the pennant-winning Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-cincinnati-reds-season] This marked the first time in team history that the Reds finished the season in last place.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-washington-senators-season] The 1901 Washington Senators won 61 games, lost 72, and finished in sixth place in the American League in its first year as a major league team.
[src:1901-washington-senators-season/1901-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Jim Manning and played home games at the American League Park I.
